{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu) 9.59–64** outlines the practice of *niyoga*, permitting a widow to bear a son through her husband's brother (brother-in-law) or a *sapiṇḍa* kinsman only when the family line faces extinction.[^1]\n\nThe appointed brother-in-law must beget **one son only** (9.60), after which their relationship ends: \"they should behave towards each other as a *guru* and a daughter-in-law\" (9.62). Some authorities allow a second son if the first fails to fulfill the purpose, but exceeding this out of lust makes both outcastes (9.61, 9.63). A widow who has borne such a son **must not be appointed to another man**, as it violates eternal Dharma, and *niyoga* is not a form of remarriage (9.64–65).[^1]\n\nThe son (*kṣetraja*) belongs to the deceased husband and inherits like an *aurasa* (legitimate) son.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 9, paragraphs p-a1e160 to p-f00094](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-a1e160).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 9* (see verses 144–147, 166–167).",
